so most of it rocks,but there is one thing that kept annoying me. &quot;i'ts cold&quot;was in ,like every other line.to repititious,try implying that its cold like saying:<br>
<br>
 &quot;The chill began in my feet and rose through my body like the updraft next to a skyscraper.&quot;<br>
 <br>
Or you could imply the temperature by describing other things,seperating the narrator and reader from the description.like this:<br>
 <br>
&quot;With great effort I exhale,expelling the little moisture in my body into the air,only to oserve the futility of its escape as it crystalizes in the air,as if telling me of things to come.&quot;<br>
 <br>
See,i set a mood,described the character/narrator,and threw in a little foreshadowing in too.The only problem with sentences like this one is that they are too rich in detail and are confusing too he reader,but in essays or stories like yours you want the reader to be confused so its perfect.<br>
 Also,you definately want to keep it in first person because the third person point of view implies even more hevily that the main character lives through the situation than the firs person point of view does,But there is something to be said for 3rd person because it allows the writer to express wisdom better because it implies that the writer has lived through the ordeal himself,though that is often not the case.<br>
 Lastly,one of the best pieces of advice,and most often heard is this: &quot;write what you know&quot;.This means ,simply,you should think of a time in your life when you felt the emotion you are trying to express,confusion and/or coldness,and write about it like your still feeling it.<br>
